Several studies investigated the role of the CCR5Δ32 polymorphism in HBV infection. Some of them found no association between those variables (
 Arababadi et al., 2010; 
 Khorramdelazad et al., 2013; 
 Safari et al., 2017; 
 Zhang et al., 2018; 
 Moudi et al., 2019). In other studies, the absence of CCR5Δ32 allele in the sample, due to ethnic features of the evaluated population, precluded the analysis concerning the potential impact of this genetic variant on HBV infection (
 Ahn et al., 2006; 
 Li et al., 2011).
